Review: Next-level sleaze right here. Charles Bronson really cornered the market in the republican wet dream genre of police action thrillers at one point. Every scene feels gross, filled with odd dialogue ("Some oriental man touched my holy of holies!") and a whole lot of stereotypes and racist tirades. You know when people say that Blazing Saddles could never be made today? They should really replace that with this film.

I much prefer Tom Berenger's rough edge in the first Substitute but Treat Williams is serviceable in a softer, less menacing version of the Substitute. This is pretty much a rehash of the first movie and there's nothing here that one-ups the crazy moments in the first.

There was so many great gags in this movie that had me laughing. The humor of this movie is very much my style. It's operating in its own world logic so the situations can be absurd as they want, such as having a store sell cardboard cutouts of celebrities for lonely guys to a bit where Steve Martin has to find Charles Grodin before he jumps off the Manhattan Bridge where several men are already jumping off the bridge. It's…

While a musical adaptation of The Color Purple is more of an admirable attempt rather than just redoing was has already been done before, this version can't seem to quite translate that broadway show seamlessly to film. I don't really want to compare this to the Spielberg original because their intentions are different, but I can't help but bring my own baggage going into this movie. I love, love, love the Spielberg version. It's such an emotional gut punch and…

I'm surprised this movie has had such a glowing reaction from people given that its weirdness goes beyond that of the weirdness you'd see in your typical A24 movie (And this is technically a Disney Film!). You know from the opening few minutes of this movie that no other film looks quite like this. The sets, the costumes, the manic camerawork, it gives a personality to the film. On a technical level, the movie just nails it. The dialogue is…

A delight from start to finish. Being a huge Wonka fan, I was a little apprehensive coming into this movie. The trailers didn't quite sell it to me at all, with a lot of time being used to sell Hugh Grant's Oompa Loompa. But lo and behold, the movie is a musical through and through, and a fantastic one at that. Chalamet gives a great take on Willy Wonka. He shines in this. The supporting cast is fantastic, with each…

Movie: I Wouldn't Be in Your Shoes

Review: Best Ernest movie so far. They seem to hit a sweet spot with this one where the story is compelling, the gags funny, and the slapstick taken to absurd levels. Whether it goes downhill from here, I'll have to see.

Movie: Mr. Monk's Last Case: A Monk Movie

Review: Truly brings the Dirty Harry Franchise to the 80s, for better or worse. "The Dead Pool" feels nothing like the other entries in the franchise, yet it follows it beat for beat at the same time. New killer, new partner, a robbery that Harry has to stop, the department just berating Harry for how he does things, the ending where the camera does the crane/helicopter zoom out shot. The Harry character is flanderized to a point where he just becomes…

Movie: Sesame Street Presents: Follow That Bird
Shriek If You Know What I Did Last Friday the Thirteenth
Review: I know comedy is subjective but if you think this movie is funnier than Scary Movie, you're crazy. There's some clever gags but it's a pretty scattershot spoof with a hell of a lot more misses. I'm pretty astonished how they got recognizable names in this from Coolio to Rose Marie to Mink Stole to Shirley Jones to make tiny appearances.

I was surprised at how simple and by the numbers the overall plot is. This isn't really different than any other hitman seeks revenge after the consequences of a botched job storyline. Fortunately, Fincher is that great a filmmaker I was still engaged and just vibing with the film. It's plays like a videogame with all the chapters and stuff. I was interested in Fassbender's character and trying to figure him out as a character as it goes on and…
I came in expecting a goofy comedy about a family running a rundown hotel. I came out absolutely flabbergasted.

The boy on the poster isn't even the love interest in this obscure coming-of-age movie from the 80s. Instead, Jennifer Connelly and Maggie Corman are pining for older guys, with questionable age gaps, a sign that this is truly the 80s where this fact isn't even brought up as a side note. I wanted to like this movie more because it has the nostalgic vibe to it. I actually dug the soundtrack. It's like a mix of pop and jingles…
